","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1169":"1169","1223":"1223","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","about 1169":"circa 1169","about 1210":"circa 1210","Isle of Wight, Hampshire, England":"Isle of Wight, Hampshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Hinton, Hampshire, England":"Hinton, Hampshire, England","Dorset, England":"Dorset, England"},"en":{"about 1169–":"about 1169–Deceased","1169–Female":"1169–Deceased","1170–1238":"1170–1238","1200–1223":"1200–1223","1210–Male":"1210–Deceased","1150–Male":"1150–Deceased","before 1199":"before 1199","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1169":"1169","1223":"1223","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","about 1169":"about 1169","about 1210":"about 1210","Isle of Wight, Hampshire, England":"Isle of Wight, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom","Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, England, United Kingdom","Hinton, Hampshire, England":"Hinton, Hampshire, England","Dorset, England":"Dorset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Damarell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman:  See  Damerell  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Damerell","meanings":["Norman: locative name from Aumale in Seine-Maritime, with fused preposition  <i>d(e)</i> ‘from’."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":46,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":55,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":90,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Margaret Damarell was born about 1169, in Hinton, Hampshire, England as the daughter of Sir William de Damerall of Hinton. She married Richard Trenchard Jr. before 1199, in Dorset, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in Hampshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1169–":"umbes 1169–Surnud","1169–Female":"1169–Surnud","1170–1238":"1170–1238","1200–1223":"1200–1223","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1150–Male":"1150–Surnud","before 1199":"enne 1199","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1169":"1169","1223":"1223","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","about 1169":"umbes 1169","about 1210":"umbes 1210","Isle of Wight, Hampshire, England":"Isle of Wight, Hampshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hinton, Hampshire, England":"Hinton, Hampshire, England","Dorset, England":"Dorset, England"},"fi":{"about 1169–":"noin 1169–Kuollut","1169–Female":"1169–Kuollut","1170–1238":"1170–1238","1200–1223":"1200–1223","1210–Male":"1210–Kuollut","1150–Male":"1150–Kuollu